1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,580
Hi everyone.

2
00:00:02,460 --> 00:00:17,380
Today I want to introduce you to a wonderful chip that has become widespread, on which you can assemble galvanically isolated converters with flyback topology — that is,

3
00:00:17,380 --> 00:00:19,220
a flyback converter.

4
00:00:20,160 --> 00:00:29,460
I got acquainted with this chip by chance during a trip to an internet acquaintance.

5
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:39,320
And there we encountered the issue that this converter was undervoltage at the output.

6
00:00:40,220 --> 00:00:49,980
Working it out in the field was unrealistic — there was no necessary equipment, and no skills for working with this chip.

7
00:00:50,160 --> 00:00:57,420
And after arriving home I decided to master it, since this chip has quite a lot of potential.

8
00:00:58,420 --> 00:01:02,800
What can be noted about this chip?

9
00:01:03,660 --> 00:01:07,860
It's made in different packages.

10
00:01:09,040 --> 00:01:13,320
I prefer to work in DIP packages.

11
00:01:13,800 --> 00:01:16,300
It's small here, 8-pin.

12
00:01:16,840 --> 00:01:22,520
There's also a surface-mount SMD version in the same kind of package.

13
00:01:22,520 --> 00:01:39,260
The main circuit elements will be the controller chip itself, the switch, the converter core, and a high-speed Schottky diode.

14
00:01:41,200 --> 00:01:51,380
I want to note that in this converter this part isn't a transformer but a kind of choke.

15
00:01:52,520 --> 00:02:03,280
On switching of the choke's primary winding with the switch, a sharp kick happens.

16
00:02:04,160 --> 00:02:17,140
The choke stores energy in the core as a magnetic field, and then during the pause dumps it into the load through the secondary winding.

17
00:02:18,760 --> 00:02:24,180
The chip has two feedbacks.

18
00:02:25,200 --> 00:02:33,380
First, voltage feedback, implemented through a PC817 optocoupler.

19
00:02:33,380 --> 00:02:38,160
And second, current feedback.

20
00:02:39,480 --> 00:02:48,760
It's done on a resistor placed in the source circuit of the FET.

21
00:02:49,560 --> 00:02:59,800
By picking this resistor's value we ultimately regulate the current passing through the switch.

22
00:02:59,800 --> 00:03:07,540
Not by limiting its resistance, but by means of feedback that goes to pin 3.

23
00:03:08,260 --> 00:03:20,920
And the chip, tracking the voltage drop across this resistor, changes the duration of the pulse driving the FET gate.

24
00:03:22,940 --> 00:03:28,180
Next, let's look at the parts suitable for building this converter.

25
00:03:29,800 --> 00:03:31,980
We've covered the chip.

26
00:03:32,520 --> 00:03:36,840
The PC817 optocoupler looks like this.

27
00:03:37,880 --> 00:03:47,920
By the way, for those who don't know how to count pins on chips or optocouplers, there's a dot on the case.

28
00:03:48,180 --> 00:03:51,900
That's pin 1 of the chip.

29
00:03:51,900 --> 00:03:56,280
I marked the dot near pin 1.

30
00:03:57,280 --> 00:04:02,320
And the optocoupler pins correspond to the drawing.

31
00:04:02,660 --> 00:04:08,960
Full pin correspondence, same as on the chip.

32
00:04:09,060 --> 00:04:15,200
Pins are counted counter-clockwise from the dot on the case.

33
00:04:16,200 --> 00:04:22,200
About the switches you can use in this circuit.

34
00:04:22,980 --> 00:04:38,700
Since our supply rating will be up to 18 V, the switch works in pulse mode and voltage spikes can appear.

35
00:04:38,700 --> 00:04:50,090
And so that this voltage spike doesn't break down the transistor, we need to choose it with some voltage margin — from 60 V.

36
00:04:50,090 --> 00:05:03,590
In this case I gave the name here — this transistor FR120N, in a package for SMD mount.

37
00:05:04,730 --> 00:05:10,710
And an IRF540 in this kind of package.

38
00:05:11,110 --> 00:05:15,710
These transistors are rated 100 V.

39
00:05:15,710 --> 00:05:17,830
Which suits us well.

40
00:05:18,050 --> 00:05:26,330
And plus they have a pretty light gate — with minimum saturation capacitance.

41
00:05:27,570 --> 00:05:29,210
Next, the diode.

42
00:05:30,190 --> 00:05:40,590
If you plan to power chips from this converter, then this diode in this package will work.

43
00:05:41,210 --> 00:05:45,010
This is a 1N5819, 1 A diode.

44
00:05:45,710 --> 00:05:57,370
And if you'll connect more serious loads to this converter, I recommend putting a diode in the larger 1N5822 package.

45
00:05:58,770 --> 00:06:00,210
It's 3 A.

46
00:06:00,790 --> 00:06:10,530
This diode is more than enough for powering a 10–15 W load — easily handles it.

47
00:06:12,470 --> 00:06:30,810
Now I need to note that the chip's power pin — here, pin 7, where plus power is applied — connects directly to the transistors that

48
00:06:30,810 --> 00:06:33,710
do the gate opening of the switch.

49
00:06:33,710 --> 00:06:41,770
That is, the supply voltage applied to pin 7 will also be at pin 6.

50
00:06:42,410 --> 00:06:48,610
So you can't exceed 20 V here.

51
00:06:48,970 --> 00:06:53,210
That's the boundary by gate breakdown.

52
00:06:53,210 --> 00:07:14,630
If by build you need this circuit to work with voltage exceeding 18 V at the input, you'll need to put either an additional limiting converter or a regulator

53
00:07:14,630 --> 00:07:18,310
on the supply to pin 7.

54
00:07:18,310 --> 00:07:29,730
If the rating suits, the regulator should be 18 V — that is, apply no more than 18 V to pin 7.

55
00:07:30,210 --> 00:07:36,370
And then you can use this chip with a higher supply rating.

56
00:07:36,550 --> 00:07:43,350
And of course turn count will need to be picked for your supply rating.

57
00:07:44,230 --> 00:07:49,630
Now about the most important part of this converter — the core.

58
00:07:50,270 --> 00:08:00,570
The thing is, the core in this circuit is subjected to unipolar pulses, which can easily bring it to saturation.

59
00:08:00,710 --> 00:08:08,030
So there are minimum dimensions of the core that'll work in this circuit.

60
00:08:09,030 --> 00:08:16,730
I picked this in practice, and the core dimensions are shown on this drawing.

61
00:08:17,830 --> 00:08:26,570
In length it's 15.5 mm, inner radius 18.5 mm, outer 29.7 mm.

62
00:08:27,070 --> 00:08:31,010
The wall width is 5.6 mm.

63
00:08:31,010 --> 00:08:34,990
You can also pick other cores.

64
00:08:36,090 --> 00:08:43,430
In principle, cores with bigger dimensions are welcome — with smaller ones the converter works worse.

65
00:08:43,670 --> 00:08:49,310
You can also use ferrite cup cores of corresponding dimensions.

66
00:08:50,290 --> 00:08:52,730
Now about the primary winding.

67
00:08:53,470 --> 00:08:59,170
Primary winding — turn count picked according to the supply voltage rating.

68
00:08:59,170 --> 00:09:04,430
In this case, the supplied voltage won't be higher than 18 V.

69
00:09:04,930 --> 00:09:08,510
Practically it'll constantly work from 12 V.

70
00:09:08,930 --> 00:09:16,410
So under this core, the optimal turn count was from 7 to 11.

71
00:09:16,490 --> 00:09:19,370
Middle value — 8-9 turns.

72
00:09:20,370 --> 00:09:30,570
If the turn count is too big, then the core, even at these dimensions, starts going into saturation.

73
00:09:31,030 --> 00:09:47,570
And if you reduce the turn count, for example to about 4 on this core, the current feedback triggers too early and the converter starts undervoltaging at the output.

74
00:09:47,570 --> 00:09:49,870
So you have to find a golden middle.

75
00:09:50,390 --> 00:09:58,690
Everyone will do this in practice by picking the turn count for their own core.

76
00:09:58,770 --> 00:10:01,910
That's a feature of these schemes.

77
00:10:04,030 --> 00:10:12,630
And further everything depends on the secondary winding — on what voltage we want to get.

78
00:10:12,630 --> 00:10:19,090
That is, if you need 5 V, then the turn count here will be about 4.

79
00:10:19,870 --> 00:10:31,090
And if, like me in this case, you need a supply rating around 16 V, that'll be 12 turns.

80
00:10:32,570 --> 00:10:37,410
So, next comes the feedback.

81
00:10:37,410 --> 00:10:45,410
I noted that the output with voltage feedback connects to the most energy-consuming section of the consumer chain.

82
00:10:46,990 --> 00:10:58,810
That is, if you assemble the circuit without this part, with you all this is fine.

83
00:10:59,130 --> 00:11:03,550
The feedback works directly on the load.

84
00:11:03,550 --> 00:11:15,550
But if you'll need to make N secondary windings on this core, then you need to follow this rule.

85
00:11:16,130 --> 00:11:28,930
Because connecting a more powerful load to one of the leads where feedback isn't done leads to a voltage drop on it.

86
00:11:28,930 --> 00:11:34,910
Since the impact on feedback through the secondary winding happens indirectly.

87
00:11:35,890 --> 00:11:40,810
So the most powerful consumer is connected at this point.

88
00:11:42,570 --> 00:11:47,930
This way stable voltage is also achieved on other windings.

89
00:11:48,690 --> 00:11:55,470
You can also see here I introduced an 18 V zener into the circuit at the output.

90
00:11:55,470 --> 00:12:13,570
The thing is, when we connect a consumer to one of this converter's windings and the PWM controller starts adapting to this load, it changes the pulse duration.

91
00:12:13,570 --> 00:12:27,950
And at pulse change in the larger direction — which usually happens when connecting a load — the voltage on the secondary windings automatically grows through inductive coupling.

92
00:12:29,330 --> 00:12:36,990
And to keep elements connected further down the circuit from breaking down, you need to add a zener here.

93
00:12:36,990 --> 00:12:46,490
In this case a 1 W zener is enough to handle this rising potential.

94
00:12:46,870 --> 00:12:56,790
At these 12-turn values, with a 10 W load here, the jump can be up to 27 V.

95
00:12:57,390 --> 00:13:02,890
And the 1 W zener handles this potential adequately.

96
00:13:04,370 --> 00:13:08,150
Don't forget about this point.

97
00:13:08,830 --> 00:13:21,390
I also added an extra choke into the circuit — this isn't a mandatory system element, you can leave it out, but it's a filter.

98
00:13:21,550 --> 00:13:31,910
For when you need to power precision devices like chips that don't tolerate supply oscillations.

99
00:13:32,890 --> 00:13:38,590
The output rating is set by this zener.

100
00:13:39,690 --> 00:13:50,930
By changing the breakdown voltage — picking a different zener — we regulate the output voltage of the whole converter.

101
00:13:51,720 --> 00:14:09,070
If I picked a 15 V zener here, then considering the optocoupler requires some voltage to trigger, the output holds about 16 V.

102
00:14:09,070 --> 00:14:21,810
If you need 5 V power, then put a 4.5 V zener here and you'll get your 5 V supply.

103
00:14:22,570 --> 00:14:29,710
At that you should reduce the secondary winding turn count of this choke.

104
00:14:29,710 --> 00:14:38,830
In this case I use this scheme for powering a bridge inverter.

105
00:14:39,470 --> 00:14:45,310
I needed independent power that goes to the master generator.

106
00:14:46,030 --> 00:14:58,150
And four separate galvanically isolated supplies that go to control four bridge switches.

107
00:14:58,150 --> 00:15:03,490
And that's why I went with a 16 V power rating.

108
00:15:04,110 --> 00:15:22,850
And if you'll build a circuit that needs different power ratings — say 5 V, 9 V — you change the secondary turn count and change the output zener rating

109
00:15:22,850 --> 00:15:28,950
that'll stably hold the voltage on your load.

110
00:15:29,410 --> 00:15:33,210
I should also say a few words about mounting rules.

111
00:15:33,650 --> 00:15:44,750
Since this is a high-frequency system, the switch operating frequency here is about 160 kHz.

112
00:15:44,750 --> 00:15:59,030
At these values on pin 4 — this frequency-setting cap of 1000 pF and a resistor that creates the necessary supply voltage on the chip's clock generator.

113
00:16:00,210 --> 00:16:10,730
You should approach assembly carefully — not allowing long wires, big distances between parts on the board.

114
00:16:10,730 --> 00:16:18,010
This can lead to unwanted high-frequency pickups and inadequate converter operation.

115
00:16:19,110 --> 00:16:24,050
In this case I assembled the circuit on this prototyping board.

116
00:16:24,050 --> 00:16:38,330
A small prototyping board like this is enough to realize the whole unit.

117
00:16:38,410 --> 00:16:40,210
Let me show its size.

118
00:16:40,930 --> 00:16:46,450
It's 6 cm by 4 cm.

119
00:16:46,450 --> 00:16:51,290
Practically half the board is taken by this unit.

120
00:16:51,790 --> 00:16:56,940
Its dimensions are 11 mounting holes by 14.

121
00:16:57,830 --> 00:17:07,390
You can notice how dense the assembly is, without any long wires.

122
00:17:07,390 --> 00:17:20,190
The zener that sets the output power rating and the 10 Ω limiting resistor are brought out.

123
00:17:20,590 --> 00:17:30,850
Then a chain of capacitors of zeners shown as 18 V on the schematic.

124
00:17:30,850 --> 00:17:45,070
And at this point we'll have the core with wound wire — 5 leads and a black wire of the primary winding.

125
00:17:45,170 --> 00:17:50,110
It'll be mounted in this position in this case.

126
00:17:53,610 --> 00:17:59,200
Now an interesting point about winding phasing.

127
00:18:00,790 --> 00:18:11,640
You can see the dots are in opposite directions — meaning the wires when winding the primary and secondary of the choke in one direction need to be swapped.

128
00:18:11,640 --> 00:18:25,540
If you don't do this, then at connection the converter will consume strongly, and incorrect winding connection will show up as heating of this diode.

129
00:18:25,660 --> 00:18:33,980
This will be palpable if you touch it with your finger — it can heat up to about 50 degrees.

130
00:18:33,980 --> 00:18:53,900
On polarity change you'll immediately see an adequate rise in output voltage, this diode will be cold, and the converter will switch to no-load economical-consumption mode at 0.02 A.

131
00:18:55,160 --> 00:19:00,240
Now you see the datasheet of this chip line on the monitor.

132
00:19:00,400 --> 00:19:01,900
Here are their names.

133
00:19:02,880 --> 00:19:10,160
They're made in different types of packages — 8-pin and 14-pin.

134
00:19:11,800 --> 00:19:17,620
The 14-pin package corresponds to the NCV3843 chip.

135
00:19:18,900 --> 00:19:21,600
Pinout is shown.

136
00:19:23,800 --> 00:19:28,910
You can use this chip — it's a full analog of the 8-pin by functionality.

137
00:19:29,760 --> 00:19:43,760
The only thing introduced here is separate power on the chip itself and separate power for the transistors that drive the FET switch.

138
00:19:44,760 --> 00:20:02,080
Total power supplied to pin 12, marked VCC, and VC — pin 11, where limited power is supplied that will further drive the FET gate.

139
00:20:02,080 --> 00:20:22,160
And you'll see pins 2, 4, 6, and 13 of the chip are marked NC, meaning no connect — those pins in the 14-pin package aren't connected.

140
00:20:22,160 --> 00:20:23,380
Connected.

141
00:20:24,380 --> 00:20:32,860
Here are the chip characteristics, for anyone interested.

142
00:20:33,200 --> 00:20:39,900
And we're interested in this system's operating logic.

143
00:20:40,900 --> 00:20:44,720
It's shown in this picture.

144
00:20:45,720 --> 00:20:47,660
Zoom in a bit.

145
00:20:49,720 --> 00:21:03,380
And you can see the main logic elements of this chip that track current and voltage are comparators.

146
00:21:03,380 --> 00:21:08,160
Here's the first comparator — its output, pin 3.

147
00:21:08,580 --> 00:21:20,420
Note that here it compares the voltage that forms 1 V on the zener with the voltage drop on this resistor in the source circuit.

148
00:21:20,420 --> 00:21:29,660
And the second comparator — our lead from the zener to pin 2.

149
00:21:29,860 --> 00:21:39,780
It compares the voltage with the 2.5 V of power that forms on the divider from the resistor.

150
00:21:39,780 --> 00:21:51,620
This way they send the processed signal to the next logic element of the chip, and the switch control is done.

151
00:21:51,760 --> 00:21:56,040
The scheme is quite simple but works without fail.

152
00:21:56,040 --> 00:22:11,720
And with the current feedback introduced into the system, protection is realized — so this converter can't be made to fail, even if shorted briefly.

153
00:22:12,080 --> 00:22:16,460
It can work in that mode for a long time.

154
00:22:18,040 --> 00:22:25,780
And the switch will be in working state.

155
00:22:28,060 --> 00:22:30,680
What else is interesting here?

156
00:22:30,880 --> 00:22:32,900
Oscillograms are shown.

157
00:22:33,940 --> 00:22:37,440
Wiring for different schematic solutions.

158
00:22:40,750 --> 00:22:50,250
Unfortunately, it's all in English, but I found one more description online.

159
00:22:54,710 --> 00:22:57,090
flakebackr01.doc site.

160
00:22:58,210 --> 00:23:04,670
Here's also a PDF file — I'll leave the link in the video description.

161
00:23:06,710 --> 00:23:12,690
This PDF was written by Dmitry Makashov from Moscow.

162
00:23:14,030 --> 00:23:23,850
He dedicated this work to flyback converters, specifically the topology of our schemes.

163
00:23:24,410 --> 00:23:38,150
Here's the description — you can get acquainted with how it works in more detail, how it's arranged, what elements, how to calculate oscillograms, various connections.

164
00:23:38,150 --> 00:23:40,190
Very useful material.

165
00:23:40,950 --> 00:23:44,790
46 pages of detailed info.

166
00:23:45,870 --> 00:23:52,770
Variants of wiring for this chip are also given.

167
00:23:53,810 --> 00:24:03,670
You can create various interesting devices, including step-up or step-down converters that can be powered from the mains.

168
00:24:08,510 --> 00:24:11,010
Formulas for calculations are visible.

169
00:24:11,090 --> 00:24:13,930
This stuff makes me sad, of course.

170
00:24:14,650 --> 00:24:24,830
For me it's simpler to run experiments in practice — but for people with a math mindset, this will be very useful.

171
00:24:25,630 --> 00:24:33,850
In particular, the author shows how primary and secondary windings should be laid in cores.

172
00:24:33,850 --> 00:24:38,830
Mounting rules will also be given.

173
00:24:46,160 --> 00:24:47,820
What else interesting?

174
00:24:48,280 --> 00:24:49,660
Formulas, formulas.

175
00:24:49,980 --> 00:24:51,420
We skip this.

176
00:24:58,330 --> 00:25:06,150
Here he examines connection topology and then calculation of circuit ratings.

177
00:25:07,810 --> 00:25:12,270
Ratings that can work here are shown.

178
00:25:13,170 --> 00:25:16,590
Identify them and find them on the schematic.

179
00:25:19,290 --> 00:25:26,470
And also mounting rules for high-frequency circuit solutions.

180
00:25:26,870 --> 00:25:31,170
In this case SMD capacitors.

181
00:25:31,170 --> 00:25:34,570
What goes in which case and how it'll work.

182
00:25:35,090 --> 00:25:41,410
Voluminous work done by Dmitry — huge thanks to him.

183
00:25:42,610 --> 00:25:45,830
Moving to checking the chip's operation.

184
00:25:46,670 --> 00:25:53,770
Assembling everything on a prototyping board except the choke.

185
00:25:55,990 --> 00:26:00,910
We start checking the chip's operation with the clock generator.

186
00:26:01,050 --> 00:26:02,330
Output 4.

187
00:26:02,690 --> 00:26:04,570
I connected a probe to it.

188
00:26:05,310 --> 00:26:09,250
And we can observe this oscillogram on the device.

189
00:26:09,870 --> 00:26:12,870
Amplitude is about 3 V.

190
00:26:13,530 --> 00:26:15,970
Frequency 161 kHz.

191
00:26:16,970 --> 00:26:25,770
Now we should check whether the signal goes to the FET gate control.

192
00:26:26,570 --> 00:26:31,950
For this, connect the probe to pin 6 of the chip.

193
00:26:32,910 --> 00:26:34,010
Connecting.

194
00:26:37,970 --> 00:26:42,530
Adjust the sweep so it's easy to examine.

195
00:26:42,530 --> 00:26:51,010
And you see the pulse frequency also corresponds to about 160 kHz.

196
00:26:53,150 --> 00:26:59,010
And you can see how the chip works with disconnected feedbacks.

197
00:26:59,170 --> 00:27:04,430
In this case it treats it as if maximum load is connected.

198
00:27:04,430 --> 00:27:11,970
The pulse duration is maximum, with small pauses between them.

199
00:27:12,850 --> 00:27:30,770
In operation, the chip will constantly change pulse duration, limiting the output ratings for voltage and current.

200
00:27:31,770 --> 00:27:43,250
We've confirmed the signal reaches the gate, and we can now turn on the choke circuit.

201
00:27:46,090 --> 00:28:01,430
If you don't connect pin 3 through the resistor that brings it to the common wire, there won't be a signal at the gate.

202
00:28:03,170 --> 00:28:17,250
And consumption in this mode, while the chip is on the test bench, is 12.1 V and 0.02 A.

203
00:28:20,610 --> 00:28:29,030
The same will practically be the idle current when we have the choke installed without loads connected.

204
00:28:30,390 --> 00:28:42,950
Now look at the voltage ratings on the finished board that will go to my internet acquaintance with whom we dealt with this chip.

205
00:28:43,590 --> 00:28:45,410
It's made for three outputs.

206
00:28:47,150 --> 00:28:56,030
One power for the master generator, where two switches should be commutated with independent power.

207
00:28:56,030 --> 00:29:10,830
So we apply 12 V at the input and see that the zener here is exactly the 15 V indicated in this schematic for feedback.

208
00:29:11,510 --> 00:29:16,390
You see the voltage is 16.4 V on one channel.

209
00:29:17,070 --> 00:29:34,750
Now switching to 16.2 V on the channel that's tracked by feedback.

210
00:29:35,230 --> 00:29:42,500
And the third output.

211
00:29:44,620 --> 00:29:46,020
Connect.

212
00:29:48,540 --> 00:29:51,200
Also 16.4 V.

213
00:29:51,400 --> 00:29:55,480
Now we conduct a crash test for the system.

214
00:29:56,320 --> 00:29:58,960
Short its outputs.

215
00:29:59,820 --> 00:30:04,940
With tweezers we do the action.

216
00:30:04,940 --> 00:30:07,860
You see — shorting on the channel.

217
00:30:10,460 --> 00:30:15,820
Voltage drops, but nothing happens to the converter.

218
00:30:15,980 --> 00:30:16,840
Second output.

219
00:30:22,380 --> 00:30:30,180
Now try to enlarge so you can see there's a short circuit.

220
00:30:34,770 --> 00:30:39,690
You can see the discharge happening.

221
00:30:39,970 --> 00:30:40,650
And the third.

222
00:30:45,530 --> 00:30:58,390
You see that while no load is connected, voltage stays on the non-shorted output channel.

223
00:30:58,390 --> 00:31:09,430
But if we short the one the multimeter is directly connected to, the voltage drops to a small value.

224
00:31:10,630 --> 00:31:14,970
After the short is removed, the system goes back to operating mode.

225
00:31:15,790 --> 00:31:30,310
Now we'll also test how changing this resistor's value affects the system's final output current.

226
00:31:30,770 --> 00:31:35,490
Recommended under this chip is 0.5 Ω.

227
00:31:35,870 --> 00:31:49,490
You can go bigger — for example, the 1 Ω resistor here — because big loads won't be connected here, just gate control and master clock generator.

228
00:31:49,490 --> 00:31:58,650
You can also go smaller — put 0.1 Ω — and then you can connect pretty serious loads here.

229
00:31:58,870 --> 00:32:03,610
But we'll test on a 12 V, 10 W lamp.

230
00:32:04,590 --> 00:32:13,310
Now we'll check the voltage feedback and the moment the chip turns on — from what potential.

231
00:32:13,310 --> 00:32:20,790
We apply 7 V at the input, you see the multimeter doesn't capture the turn-on moment.

232
00:32:21,450 --> 00:32:24,290
It'll be about 8 V.

233
00:32:25,310 --> 00:32:28,110
Voltage is rising.

234
00:32:33,920 --> 00:32:41,600
8 V — and at 8.2 V the chip turned on.

235
00:32:41,600 --> 00:32:47,100
So this converter can quite work from a 9 V battery.

236
00:32:48,540 --> 00:32:53,220
And we see the output voltage is 16.3 V.

237
00:32:53,440 --> 00:33:03,940
Now let's raise the voltage further — about 18 V — and we'll see the chip's output voltage stabilizes.

238
00:33:08,020 --> 00:33:08,960
Raise...

239
00:33:08,960 --> 00:33:14,820
Watch the rating on the multimeter and see it doesn't change.

240
00:33:18,810 --> 00:33:21,390
This is idle consumption current.

241
00:33:34,310 --> 00:33:36,730
Practically we have 19 V.

242
00:33:37,950 --> 00:33:45,030
Already working on the edge of FET gate breakdown.

243
00:33:46,030 --> 00:33:54,610
We won't raise higher, but we've confirmed this chip clearly holds the output voltage.

244
00:33:55,670 --> 00:34:00,770
Now we look at how the current protection behaves.

245
00:34:01,610 --> 00:34:07,270
You see I soldered several resistors here and they're not closed.

246
00:34:07,270 --> 00:34:17,290
I'll put resistors in parallel with this resistor, thereby reducing its value.

247
00:34:18,570 --> 00:34:21,630
The resistor in the circuit is now 1 Ω.

248
00:34:21,790 --> 00:34:31,010
These are also 1 Ω resistors — connecting two in parallel gives 0.5 Ω, and so on toward reduction.

249
00:34:33,350 --> 00:34:35,310
Turn on the converter.

250
00:34:35,910 --> 00:34:42,810
The multimeter shows 4.8 V on this lamp.

251
00:34:45,130 --> 00:34:53,190
The voltage feedback is tuned to 15 V, and now it lets the chip work.

252
00:34:53,330 --> 00:34:57,850
And here the current feedback reduces pulse duration.

253
00:34:57,850 --> 00:35:03,290
Now I reduce the resistance — add 1 Ω in parallel.

254
00:35:04,450 --> 00:35:18,830
You see when 0.5 Ω is connected, the voltage at this point grew to 9.9 V.

255
00:35:19,290 --> 00:35:22,330
Now connecting one more resistor,

256
00:35:28,080 --> 00:35:35,980
and we get the value 11.82, and so on.

257
00:35:36,140 --> 00:35:44,700
Reducing this resistor's value lets you raise the voltage on the load.

258
00:35:45,610 --> 00:35:47,240
Same effects.

259
00:35:47,480 --> 00:35:55,400
That's the output voltage we looked at on the channel with feedback.

260
00:35:56,400 --> 00:36:05,940
The same can be demonstrated on another output channel of the converter.

261
00:36:08,840 --> 00:36:12,780
Say, this one without feedback installed.

262
00:36:12,780 --> 00:36:27,740
You also see 4.9 V, then 9.9 V, and here 10.5 V.

263
00:36:28,320 --> 00:36:33,200
That is, through inductive coupling there's a small difference.

264
00:36:33,740 --> 00:36:47,580
But since this system works for powering chips and small consumers, it suits us fine.

265
00:36:51,470 --> 00:37:14,350
Summarizing the experiments, you can say this chip series is a good solution when we need to make a converter with galvanic isolation and a system

266
00:37:14,550 --> 00:37:19,070
that clearly tracks output voltage.

267
00:37:19,750 --> 00:37:35,370
During various tests I didn't notice a single failure of this chip — voltage rose, I tested it for powering chips, all was in order.

268
00:37:37,230 --> 00:37:42,590
That is, you can build and assemble various devices and use it.

269
00:37:44,070 --> 00:37:50,170
On that note — thanks to everyone who watched, successful experiments and all the best.
